The MK1 series, developed by Primary Weapons Systems, is a significant product improvement for the M4/M16-type carbines and rifles. Utilizing our proven long stroke piston system, the MK1 series greatly reduces fouling in the action of the weapon making it as reliable as the AK47 that it was designed after. 

The MK1 series has been used in Iraq and Afghanistan, and has gained wide popularity with security personnel, law enforcement and civilians alike. 

The origins of the MK1 series began with the fascination in the simplicity and reliability of the AK47 combined with a deep-rooted appreciation for the ergonomics of the M4/M16 platform. Having a significant understanding of the deficiencies in the direct gas impingement operating system found on conventional M4/M16-style weapons, PWS developed the MK1 series with the professional in mind. 

Significant improvements have been made over both the direct gas impingement operating system and previous offerings of piston-driven operating systems. The product improvements made by PWS have addressed reliability and performance issues as well as reduced carrier tilt, cam pin wear and carrier bounce. In addition, we have one of the lightest systems on the market today! 

An innovative hand guard system utilizes a proprietary non-free float system that allows the end user or unit armorer to replace individual rails as needed without removing the barrel, barrel nut or even other rails. This system allows the user to attach numerous Picatinny rail-mounted devices such as sights, lights, and laser aiming devices. 

The PWS proprietary operating system utilizes an operating rod that is attached to the carrier and a floating head piston that is attached to the operating rod. The MK1 series is built to be a true combat carbine. With no unnecessary gas adjustments and only one moving assembly, this is the most rugged, simple and versatile piston operating system available.

location: Loudoun, Fairfax, Clarke, Northern Virginia, Virginia
postcontent:
http://www.assaultweb.net/forums/showthread.php?t=49021

"The CZ 40B began life a few years ago as a joint venture between Colt and CZ to help Colt get its foot back into the police firearms market, so the story goes. The gun is a dedicated built-from-the-ground-up .40 caliber - not an adaptation of a 9mm frame. They made it with an alloy frame, a double stack mimic of the 1911 grip frame style, and the Sig-style locking system. It's only commonality with the CZ 75/85 series pistols lies in the use of the CZ 75/85 double/single action trigger, the CZ 75/85 sear blocking safety, and the CZ 75B magazines. All else is brand spankin' new. The gun was first produced by CZ for Colt as the Z40 and had a newly-designed DAO trigger at that time.

Colt was not able to continue marketing the gun and had to back out of its end of the deal. So CZ replaced the trigger in what had been the Colt Z40, made some other changes, and began marketing the gun as the CZ 40B."

postcontent:
This is an original 1955 Willy's Military Jeep, the M38-A1 Model, it is the REAL DEAL, it is not a fake, copy or reproduction. It has the original Willy's stamp on the firewall under the hood. This jeep is in excellent condition, mechanically sound, runs and drives GREAT!! Absolutely nothing wrong with this jeep mechanically or cosmetically. I did a mechanical overhaul on this jeep so it has all of the new regular stuff it would need, brakes, brake lines, fuel lines, spark plugs, wires, distributor cap, alternator, solenoid, ect, ect. 4 wheel drive (must lock front wheels to engage 4 wheel drive), 3 speed, low and high gears, transfer case, can NOT get stuck in this thing!! Jeep is is equipped with an ammo can as a glove box, cb radio with speaker, military police siren, blackout light. I have many miscellaneous extra parts to go with it. It has a gas can mount on the side and I have extra gas cans to go with it.

I can not guarantee that this jeep was in the Korean War but it was built at the end of the war, also the military cut it in half for shipping purposes and welded it back together. I also have roll bar, canvas top and doors for it (not shown in pictures). I did this jeep as a U.S. Army military police scenario, it is lots and lots of fun. I am in not hurry at all to sell it and am more interested in someone taking good care of this jeep as I have. If you are trying to make a profit off of me and this jeep than please don't waste my time. I want somebody to appreciate it as much as I have. When I got insurance on this jeep, they told me it was worth $8,000 in it's worst condition and $16,600 in it's best condition. I would guess that it falls somewhere in the middle but I have it insured for $8,000. Like I said, I am in no hurry at all to sell it so if you are interested please make me an offer. I am willing to do a cash sale or a trade and cash sale or just a straight trade if the price is right. E-mail me your offers, you never know you just might have something I can't live without. I live in Oklahoma so the jeep will need to be hauled back on a trailer.

title: For Sale:  Colts Patents Arms Manufacturing Company.
postcontent: This my Colt letter from Kurt Ruger Vogel (Ruger's grandson) have been added. I could not add the FTJ bio info as I discovered it was copyrighted. However,during the early 1900s Frank Tenney Johnson worked and sketched on a cattle ranch near Hayden, Colorado,attended an early Frontier Days celebration in Cheyenne, Wyoming, and ventured south to Navajo country. All of this influenced both his career and his personal life. It was possibly during this time that he obtained this Colt.) This gun is from the William Ruger Collection and was purchased from his grandson. It is reported to have belonged to Frank Tenney Johnson, a famous Western artist active at the same time as Russell and Remington. The .41 Colt, the holster and gun belt, and the display case are all from the Ruger Collection. Also included, is a framed authenticated print of a 1936 Frank Tenney Johnson painting, "On the Range", which was added at a later date. The gun is in excellent mechanical condition and fine cosmetic condition. Case hardening remains on the hammer and frame and the original blue has thinned except on the barrel next to the frame. All serial numbers match, except the loading gate which, as is normal, has an assembly number, and the grips fit well, but are worn. The holster has a tear at the muzzle end, probably from being drawn repeatedly. There are some "dings" on the barrel just forward of the ".41 Colt", and I have no idea what may have caused them. It is apparent that Tenney did not leave this weapon in a closet. This weapon would be an outstanding acquisition for a collector who can display it properly. I cannot, and hence, am selling it to someone who can showcase it as it deserves. The gun was manufactured in 1899 and an FFL is required for shipment.
